diff:1619236783:1619236783:=1,44d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Expansion: More Examples of Presentatives - and their uses in verbs%0a%3c :Author: nithyas%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.DativePresentativesInKentuckyEnglishAndDerivatives|DativePresentativesInKentuckyEnglishAndDerivatives]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.TimG|TimG]]%0a%3c :Section: D%0a%3c :Completed: 23.04.2021 - 20:59%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c As mentioned in your article, the use of the presentative is common in many Southern dialects of American English. As someone from a region where these dialects are common, I found it interesting that while the dative presentative is not as common in my regional dialects, the addition of the dative to a verb instead is much more common.%0a%3c %0a%3c For example, phrase construction like, "I love me some country music" or "I need to get me some new shoes" are common.%0a%3c %0a%3c The article you linked also  mentions that this kind of construction is largely rejected in the North, and even to me, a sentence like "Here’s him a nice cup of coffee" sounds a little strange. One way to think about it, however, is the dative presentative is just a different syntax for a preposition. For example, "Here’s him a nice cup of coffee" is meant to convey "Here’s a nice cup of coffee for him", which would be considered more grammatical by most people.%0a%3c %0a%3c Here are some more examples of the dative: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/personal-datives%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
